"Yes, sir. They should be en route now, we gave them time to get rations from the mess." Exactly at 5:00, the Exodus company was gathered at the vehicle park. Shaw climbed onto a crate and began to speak.
"We are deploying to FOB I-131, eighty kilometers from Ianlos. We must support the ongoing siege and the upcoming attack on Ianlos to crush the insurrection. From there, we will have an advanced position and a base at the foot of the mountains," explained Shaw. "Gather your units, and board."
The company dispersed, each joining their unit, and the sergeants made them get on the tanks. Cohren climbed aboard one of the armored vehicles, at the front of the convoy, and joined Nemic, Craith, and two new recruits. Cohren remembered their arrival a few days earlier, but he knew little about them. Sitting on the side, legs dangling, he adjusted his pack and his radio equipment, which was connected to his earpiece and throat microphone.
"Hey Cohren, does Harris still have Snowball?" asked Nemic as they settled in.
"You mean the chicken he stole?" Cohren remembered the morning they had stolen it from a farm. "Yes, I'm sure of it."
Cohren glanced toward one of the tanks and spotted Harris with his unit. From the back of his pack, he could just make out the movement of a small chicken shaking its head to observe the surroundings.
"Yeah, he always has," replied Cohren as the tank's turret opened with a clicking sound to allow his commander to pass through.
"All the tanks were on the move," declared the commander calmly, but clearly in his helmet. The engines of a squad of tanks and Strykers roared as they began to advance. The Kronos that Cohren was on jolted as its brakes were released and it began to move into formation. The tanks spread out in a V to cross the plains of Itania. The winter storms had frozen the swamps and forests, but the mud was still there.
After about an hour, one of the new recruits, whose name Cohren remembered as Orson, spoke up. "Lieutenant, have you been here since the beginning of the war, isn't that right?"
"Yeah, Operation Firestorm," replied Cohren. "We thought we could finish it in a few weeks, but... we underestimated them."
"Underestimating is a weak word," said Nemic as he joined the conversation. "They had more weapons and men than we anticipated. They managed to destroy the UFS Revenant within the first two weeks, and Erebus last month. Christ, we should see it from where we are."
"Well, I'll stand by the Federation," said Orson a bit provocatively. "I won't let these terrorists scare me."
"You say that now, but from experience, I know that the new recruits of 18 like you take cover the moment they hear a shot," declared Craith.
"I think we'll be soon informed," said Corhen as he laughed. Orson didn't respond to the conversation.
"Exodus XO, Exodus CO," crackled Cohren's radio. "We detect thermal signatures approximately 300 meters away, 20 degrees right."
Cohren climbed to the top of the char and put on his optical glasses. By activating the thermal vision, he could see thermal signatures in the distance.
"Ouep, I see them," replied Cohren via his throat mic.
"Enemies?" asked the other recruit, Natayla.
"Can't tell for sure," declared Cohren. He activated his mic and said: "Exodus Company, don't fire unless we fire on you, make them come out."
As they approached, the small thermal signatures changed from blurry spots to more distinct shapes. As they got closer, one of them ran toward something, picked it up, and then rushed back to the small ridge where they were. The silhouettes took positions to fire.
"We have contacts," Shaw cried into the radio, as orange tracers were fired from the ridge. The bullets ricocheted off the sides of the tanks, while the soldiers jumped from their vehicles to take cover behind them. A anti-tank missile whizzed by and crashed to the ground behind the formation, exploding and sending debris flying onto one of the vehicles. Another missile hit the side of a Stryker, an APS-Cerberus, and exploded. Its crew emerged and dove for cover as the ammunition ignited.
"Iron 1-2 and &-", 25 degrees right, 275 meters. "Fire," shouted the tank platoon commander into the radio. Iron 1-2 and 1-3 opened fire, their shells flew toward the ridge and exploded, sending mud and stones into the air.
"Send the Senti," cried Knoxx, who was observing the ridge through his binoculars. The back of one of the Cerberus opened and a disarmed soldier wearing a special helmet emerged. He barked orders into a square microphone and two Senti, or Sentinels by their official name, rushed outside. Their thin, metallic arms and legs swung forward as they sprinted. They were armed, but their weapons were attached to their backs.
"Do we kill them or capture them?", asked Craith as they watched them.
"It seems we are capturing them," advanced Cohren as the two Sentinels disappeared into a cloud of ash and smoke. Shouts and gunfire echoed from the ridge, but ceased quickly. A moment later, the two Sentinels returned, dragging someone behind them, whose boots dragged along the ground. Once safe with the squad, they threw the individual to the ground. He groaned in pain as he collapsed into the mud and snow.
Shaw walked towards the individual, who was beginning to get up. He turned to one of the Sentinels. "How many?"
"Three dead, leader," said the Sentinel. "The others fled on foot."
Shaw nodded and turned to Cohren and Craith, who were standing beside him. "Both of you, would you be so kind as to rid us of this man?"
